<p><b>Apma</b> (or <b>Abma</b>) is the language of central <a href="/wiki/Pentecost_Island" title="Pentecost Island">Pentecost island</a> in <a href="/wiki/Vanuatu" title="Vanuatu">Vanuatu</a>. Apma belongs to the <a href="/wiki/East_Vanuatu_languages" title="East Vanuatu languages">East Vanuatu languages</a>, a branch of the <a href="/wiki/Austronesian_languages" title="Austronesian languages">Austronesian languages</a> family.</p>
<p>With an estimated 7,800 native speakers (in the year 2000), Apma is the most widely spoken of Pentecost's native languages, and the fifth largest vernacular in Vanuatu as a whole. In recent times Apma has spread at the expense of other indigenous languages such as <a href="/wiki/Sowa_language" title="Sowa language">Sowa</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ske_language" title="Ske language">Ske</a>. Apma is increasingly mixed with words and expressions from <a href="/wiki/Bislama" title="Bislama">Bislama</a>, Vanuatu's national language.</p>
