<p>The dual or plural form of "you" is occasionally used in place of the singular form to show extreme respect.</p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Apma_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Nouns">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Nouns">Nouns</span></h3>
<p>Nouns in Apma are generally not preceded by <a href="/wiki/Article_(grammar)" title="Article (grammar)">articles</a>. <a href="/wiki/Plural" title="Plural">Plurality</a> is indicated by placing the pronoun <i>nii</i> ("them") or a number after the noun:</p>
<dl>
<dd><i>bwihil</i> = [the] bird</dd>
<dd><i>bwihil nii</i> = [the] birds</dd>
<dd><i>bwihil katsil</i> = three birds</dd>
</dl>
<p>Nouns may be either <b>free</b>, or <b>directly possessed</b>. Directly possessed nouns are suffixed to indicate whom an item belongs to. For example:</p>
<dl>
<dd><i>dale<b>k</b></i> = my voice</dd>
<dd><i>dale<b>m</b></i> = your voice</dd>
<dd><i>dale<b>n</b></i> = his/her voice</dd>
<dd><i>dale<b>n</b> subu</i> = the chief's voice</dd>
<dd><i>dale<b>kte</b></i> = voice (generic)</dd>
</dl>
<p>Possession may also be indicated by the use of <b>possessive classifiers</b>, separate words that occur before or after the noun and take possessive suffixes. These classifiers are:</p>
<ul>
<li><i>no-</i> for general possessions (<i>nok watang</i>, "my basket")</li>
<li><i>bila-</i> for things that are cared for, such as crops and livestock (<i>bilada bo</i>, "our pig")</li>
<li><i>ka-</i> for things to be eaten (<i>kam tsi</i>, "your sugarcane")</li>
<li><i>ma-</i> for things to be drunk (<i>maa sileng</i>, "their water")</li>
<li><i>na-</i> for associations, over which the possessor has no control (<i>vini nak</i>, "my home island")</li>
</ul>
<p>The possessive suffixes are as follows:</p>
<table class="wikitable">
<tr>
<th>Person</th>
<th>Apma<br />
(Suru Mwerani dialect)</th>
